AR(1): one time shock

  • Write a function that simulates an AR(1) process. Assume that theres a single shock in the first period. That is, simulate

\[ \begin{cases} y_t = 0 \qquad \quad \text{ for} \, t \leq 0, \\ y_t = \epsilon \qquad \quad \text{ for} \, t = 1, \\ y_{t} = \rho y_{t-1} \qquad \text{for} \, t > 1, \end{cases} \]

for \(\epsilon \sim F(\epsilon)\). Plot the output of your function.

AR(1): one time shock solution

ar1_onetime <- function(rho, maxIter = 100, shock = rnorm(1)) { 
  out    <- numeric(length = maxIter)
  out[1] <- 0 
  out[2] <- shock
  i      <- 2 
  while (out[i] > 1e-3) {
    i      <- i + 1
    out[i] <- rho * out[i-1]
    if (i == maxIter) {
      break
    } 
  }
  return(out[1:(i-1)])
}

AR(1): one time shock solution

plot(ar1_onetime(0.9, shock = 0.5), type = "l", xlab = "t", ylab = "y", 
     col = "black", main = "AR(1)")
lines(ar1_onetime(0.8, shock = 0.5), type = "l", col = "blue")
lines(ar1_onetime(0.95, shock = 0.5), type = "l", col = "red")
legend(x = "topright", legend=c("rho = 0.8", "rho = 0.9", "rho = 0.95"),
       col=c("blue", "black", "red"), cex=0.8, lty = 1)

AR(1)

  • Write a function that simulates an AR(1). That is, for \(0 \leq t \leq T\), simulate

\[ \begin{cases} y_t = y_0 \quad \qquad \qquad \text{ for} \, t = 0, \\ y_{t} = \rho y_{t-1} + \sigma \epsilon_t \qquad \text{for} \, t > 0, \end{cases} \]

for \(\epsilon \sim F(\epsilon)\).

AR(1): solution

ar1 <- function(rho, T = 100, sig = 0.1, y0 = 0.0) { 
  out    <- numeric(length = T)
  out[1] <- y0
  for (i in 2:T){ 
    out[i] <- rho * out[i - 1] + sig * rnorm(1)
  } 
  return(out)
}

AR(1): solution

x <- ar1(0.9); y <- ar1(0.0); z <- ar1(0.99)
plot(x, type = "l", xlab = "t", ylab = "y", col = "black", lty = 1,
     ylim=range(min(min(x),min(y),min(z)),max(max(x),max(y),max(z))))
lines(y, type = "l", col = "blue", lty = 2)
lines(z, type = "l", col = "red", lty = 3)
legend(x = "topleft", legend=c("rho = 0.0", "rho = 0.9", "rho = 0.99"),
       col=c("blue", "black", "red"), cex=0.8, lty = c(2,1,3))

AR(1): Monte carlo simulations

  • Simulate many times the AR(1) process with same \(T\), \(\rho\) and \(\sigma\). Plot the resulting time series, as well as the mean value of all the time series for each time period

AR(1): Monte carlo simulations solution

T    <- 60; nsim <- 50; rho = 0.95; y0 = 2.0
mat  <- matrix(nrow = T, ncol = nsim)
for (i in 1:nsim) { 
  mat[,i] <- ar1(rho, y0 = y0, T = T)
}
ar_mean <- rowMeans(mat)

AR(1): Monte carlo simulations solution

plot(mat[,1],type="l", ylim = c(min(mat),max(mat)), xlab = "t", col = rgb(0,0,0,alpha=0.1))
lines(ar_mean, col = "blue", lwd = 2)
lines(y0 * rho^(0:(T-1)), col = "red", lty = 1)
for (i in 2:nsim){ 
  lines(mat[,i],type="l", col = rgb(0,0,0,alpha=0.1))
}
